    "narrative": "Our primary offensive thrust today centers on **Cal Raleigh** (70.13) and **Geraldo Perdomo** (69.12), both of whom capitalize on high-leverage spots. **Cal Raleigh** benefits from a strong platoon advantage against Liberatore and a favorable #2 hole placement, while **Geraldo Perdomo** remains our most critical play for stolen base upside; facing M\u00e1rquez\u2019s inflated 5.26 xERA, **Geraldo Perdomo** is perfectly positioned to exploit the base paths despite a minor drag from platoon splits. **Will Smith** (68.08) and **Bryson Stott** (66.28) round out our top-tier tier, with **Bryson Stott** specifically gaining a massive 13% boost from his matchup against Bryce Elder, providing a high floor for a middle infielder who typically thrives against right-handed sinker-ballers.\n\nWhile **Taylor Ward** (59.23) and **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** (59.86) landed just outside the 60+ \"Strong\" threshold, they remain essential starts. **Taylor Ward** leverages a significant park factor boost, effectively muting the risk posed by Crochet\u2019s elite-level pitching profile. Conversely, **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez** faces a stiff test against Gausman, but his consistency anchors our lineup despite a poor historical BvP. The most contentious bench decision involved **Yainer Diaz** (51.72), who fell short of the starting rotation primarily due to his lower-order lineup projection (assumed #8). While **Yainer Diaz** projected better than **Daulton Varsho** (45.72) and **Jeremiah Jackson** (45.71) in raw efficiency, the lack of official lineup confirmation for **Yainer Diaz** created enough volatility to favor the more established high-leverage spots occupied by our outfielders today.\n\nWe must remain vigilant regarding the \"Lineup Pending\" statuses for **Will Smith**, **Bryson Stott**, **Geraldo Perdomo**, and **Gavin Sheets**. Any late shifts in the batting order, particularly for **Geraldo Perdomo** or **Will Smith**, could necessitate a quick pivot to ensure